ton M 35\nPotomac Savings Bank 15 71\nSec Sav A Coml Bk 471 500\nSeventh Street .31*\nUnited States *3\u00ae 3\nWash Mechanics 54 1....\nFire Insurance Steebs I\nAmerican I*2o\nCorcoran fl*\u00ae f....\u00bb\nFiremen\u2019s I 32 I 38\nNational Union I 22 121\nTitle Insurance Stocks I 1\nColumbia I *HI 12\nReal Estate I*s 175\nTitle A Inv Md com I 20 130\nMlacellaneoue Btneka l I\nBarber A Rosa com. 15 I II\n\u2022Chevy Chase Dairy i>fd....1102 1102\nCol. Sand A Gravel Pfd I i 24\nD C Paper pf<l 110 1..\nDiet Nat Sec Pfd I 70 \u2019l*\nEmer Bromo-Sels A I 20 1 33\nFed Storage pfd \u2019llO <125\nFed-Am Co Com ..I 21 i3*\nFed-Am Co pfd I 1101\n\u2022Lans ton Monotype -..I 11 jll?\nMer Tr A Stge con 105 110\nMer Tr A Stge pfd I >5%1100\nMergenthaler Linotype *7%\nNatl Mtge A Inv pfd I 6 1%\nPeople* Drug 8 prd 1102% 105\nReal Eat M A G pfd...... 1%\nSecurity Storage 112 111\nTer Ref A Wh Corp 47 12\nThe Carpel Corp 23 i 24\nW Meeh Mtge Com 8%l\nWash Med Bldg Corp I*\nWdwd A Lothrop ptd.<..-. 107 'll2\nEx-dividend.\nBankers Review U. S.\nHome Products\nHomblower and Weeks, mem\nbers of the New York Stock Ex\nchange, have prepared a special\nanalysis of the American Home\nProducts Corporation. The re\nview states:\n\u201cIt is our understanding that\nearnings during the currert\nyear compare very favorably\nwith a year ago, and the proba\nbility is that 1936 will esUb\u201dsh\nanother new -ecrod from the\nstandpoint of both sales and\nearnings.\u201d\nRising Bond Prices\nProve Tempting to\nCautious Investor\nThe bond market is beckoning\nto the cautious Investor. Employ\nment for his funds at 5 and 6\nper eent is offered while he awaits\nstabilization of the stock market.\nThe listed bond market has\nbeen edging further into hew high\nground for this year. Activity has\nbeen gradually picking up. Prices\non the whole have recovered to a\nlevel comparable with the closing\nmonths of 1928.\nThis recovery has not been\nsharp, ju&t a few cents each day\non the average, but weight is\nbeing added to the old and often\nproved adage that history repeats\nitself.\nHistory Reneats\nIn all past periods of business\ndepression gnd market deflation a\nrising bond* market has preceded\nan upturn in business and stocks.\nThe reason for this is simple.\nBond market prices are governed\nchiefly by money rates, except, of\ncourse, in the case of convertible\nbonds or those bearing stock-pur\nchase warrants, which are in\nfluenced by stock movements.\nIn boom times, when money is\nin demand and interest rates\nhigh, bonds are lower. Bond prices\nare forced down until the investor\nreceives a return as great, if not\ngreater, than interest rates on\nloans.\nIn times of business recession\nand stock-market deflation, money\ngoes begging. Interest rates of\n2 and 3 per cent and even lower\nbecome general.\nThe money is diverted to the\nbond market. Banks and institu\ntions are the buyers first, then\nthe individual and prices go up.\nThis is what bond prices are do\ning now. The steadiness of this\nadvance is one of the most en\ncouraging, features of the present\nconfused situation.\nRecord of 1920 21\nBack in 1920-21*\u2014the years so\nfrequently compared with 1929-30\n\u2014bonds scraped bottom in the\ngoes another record!\nLOS ANGELES NEW YORK\nHAWKS IN THE TEXACO 13\nHAWLEY IN A NEW BUICK 8\nANOTHER coast-to-coast record toppled faster than the fastest train time, is a mighty\n21. within a week! First Hawks, and now tribute to the stamina of the man, the car and\nHawley, clip hours from the best previous the crack-proof Texaco Golden Motor Oil\ntranscontinental time. The one in the air, which cooled and lubricated the tireless\nFACTS the other over the road. w Stu\u201d Hawley in a engine throughout the grueling drive.\nL\u00abft New York aty, Aug. 14,12 w)i stock Buick Eight-66S set a new east-to-west The same new and better Texaco Gasoline\nand return rec rd beating the amazing and crack-proof Texaco Motor (Ml which\np.m. (Pacific standard Time). time established by \"Cannon Ball\u201d Baker HaWley used is available at Texaco Service\nSu 2?^AniiiZ*4:46\u2019itooro U more th n hours. Stations ih all our 48 States.\nXJTsSXJ a!P M Thi renwk\u00abWe run, seventeen hours THE TEXAS COMPANY, PmAku\nArrived New York City, Aug. Is, 9:45 v\nP.M. (Eastern Standard Time) HiHB BE\nTotal west to east time 69:20 hours\ntime for trip\nnever the car but took H\non relief driven for abort dtotancee. x\u00dfk\nGASOLINE-MOTOR OIL\nTbo MutfouW My\nsummer of 1920, but the decline\nin stocks wks carried through un\ntil the summer of 1921. Bonds\nstarted to move forward in 1920\nand reached their peak in 1922.\nFor three yean the bond market\nfollowed a-fairly even course.\nStocks did not make much\nheadway from their low point in\n1921 until late in 1922, after\nbonds had reached the top of\ntheir swing. The next year\u2014\n1923\u2014witnessed little change in\nstocks from the improved levels\nreached in 1922, and it was not\nuntil late in 1924 that the buU\nmarket that died last faU got\nunderway.\nEasy Money Assured\nConditions point to a continua\ntion of the present upward trend\nin bond prices.\nThe Federal Reserve authorities\nare committed to an easy money\npolicy\u2014that is, to make available\nto business and agriculture the\nlowest possible credit rates.\nGold exports are being offset\nby Federal Reserve purchase of\nGovernment securities. This pre\nvents narrowing of the credit\nbase.\nThere is one unfavorable condi\nof a rush for loans for industrial\nexpansion and stock market spec\nulation.\nThereis one unfavorable condi\ntion, which I pointed out earlier\nin the year. Bank loans on secur\nities to individuals are high, al\nthough some reduction in these\nloans has been made in recent\nThe Investor in high grade\nbonds at current levels is assured\nof an adequate interest return on\nhis money, with excellent chances\nfor appreciation in value of his\nholdings. But in bonds, as in\nstocks, care must be exercised in\nbuying Not all bonds are good\nbonds. To wit\u2014the obligations of\nmany of the foreign government\nissues. The most recent case is\nMexico-\nFRIDAY, AUGUST 98, IMO\nPfIODUCTION IN\nCOAL DROPS\nProduction of coal in New\nMexico in 1929 amounted to\n2,622,769 net tons, according to\nstatement just issued by the\nUnited States Bureau of Mines,\nDepartment of Commerce. In\ncomparison with the previous\nyear, this is decrease of 89,082\ntons, or 3.3 per cent.\nThe greater part of this de\ncline is accounted for by reduced\noutput in Colfax county where\nproduction declined from 1,663,349\ntons in 1928, to 1,451,860 tons in\n1929, a decrease of 12.7 per cent.\nThis decrease was partly offset\nby a substantial gain in McKin\nley county where production in\ncreased from 770,844 tons in 1928\nto 933,467 tons in 1929. Colfax\ncounty still remains by far the\nmost important coal producer in\nthe State, accounting for 55.4\nper cent of the total output.\nThe total value of the coal pro\nduced by the mines in New\nMexico in 1929 was $8,314,000, or\nan average value of $3.17 per\nton, which was slightly less than\nthat of 1928 when the average\nvalue was reported at $3.18. In\n1929 there were 3,233 men em\nployed in the coal Industry of\nthe State, as compared with 3,441\nmen in the previous year. The\naverage number of days worked\nin 1929 was 214 days, as against\n213 days in 1928.\n$1,1)00,000,000 Stock\nInsurance Planned\nK $1,000,000,000 stock insurance\nsyndicate of 200 insurance com\npanies has been proposed by\nFranklin Johnson, an insurance\nbroker, according to the Specta\ntor, an insurance publication.\nThe plan calls for a policy\nwhich wo l 'ld protect investors\nagainst losses in about 300 se\nlected securities. It would cover\nthem against losses they might\ninsur from inability to sell stocks\nat cost during depressions.\nAnalytes\ni'\nIP sB?\ni 111\nDR. JULIUS KIAIN\nASSISTANT SEC ft KT ARY\nOF COMMERCE, whose anal\nysis of the general business sit\nuation appeared today. The\nsurvey showed that a majority\nof the bankers of the country\nbelieve that \"good times\u201d will\nreturn in October.\nBusiness Machine\nMan Is Optimistic\nOptimistic signs are on .the hori\nzon for business, both in the\nUnited States and Europe, J. H.\nBarringer, vice president and gen\neral manager of tha. National\nCash Register factory there and\nthe installation of 450 men in the\nnew structure Was one of Bar\nringer\u2019s jobs while in Germany.\nGermany, he declares, is coming\nback nicely. National Cash Regis\nter business in Great Britain is\nthe largest in history. France\nalso is a bright spot in European\nNational Cash Register business,\naccording to Barringer.\nf\u2014\nNEW PIPE LINE\nIS STARTED\nConstruction of the Greenville-\nGreenwood pipe line, through\nwhich natural gas will be con\nducted from the main Loulslana-\nMemphis pipe line of Memphis\nNatural Gas Company to several\ncities and towns in Mississippi,\nwas started today, according to\nannouncement at D. C. Shaffer,\ngeneral manager of Memphis Na\ntural Gas Company.\nIncluded among the communl-'\nties to be served with natural\ngas through the new line are\nLeland, Indianola, Morehead, Itta\nbena and Greenwood.\nPart of tha cost of the line\nwill be borne by Memphis Natural\nGas Company and part by Mis\nsissippi Power and Light Com\npany. Distribution systems in\nthe various communities win be\nconstructed and operated by the\nMississippi Power and Light Com\npany.\nMERGENTHALER LIN'OTTFK CO.\nBrooklyn. N. Y.. Auguat 1\u00bb, ISM.\nDIVIDEND Na IM.\n'A tauteMy dirldMd lI.M upon Meh et tko IM,-\n004 iharw of prMont outiUadtng Mock of an Ht rtl\nu* of Mortontbalnr Ltootypo Company win bo paid\non Saptombor 34. ISM. |o tha itockboldon as tanort\nat thoy appear a* tb* etoia of bualnoia an Soptambar\n3, 1834. The Tnnefor Books will not bn eloeeg.\nGEO L. SCHARFFENBERGER. Treaaurer.\nFMBsr&BaMM\nNewYask NsvMmn\nMsasbsssNaw Yask Seasit\nBzshaag* aad atkar\n14MKS\u00abMrtN.V.\